  "text": "The inter-broker replication protocol in Apache Kafka is implemented across multiple components that work together to maintain replica synchronization and consistency. Here are the key components found in the codebase:\n\n## Core Replication Components\n\n**ReplicaFetcherThread** (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/ReplicaFetcherThread.scala) is the main thread that followers use to fetch data from the leader. It extends AbstractFetcherThread and handles the fetching of records, log truncation based on leader epoch, and updating high watermarks and log start offsets.\n\n**LeaderEpochFileCache** (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/epoch/LeaderEpochFileCache.java) is a critical component that caches leader epoch information in memory while persisting it to disk via LeaderEpochCheckpointFile. It manages the mapping between epochs and their corresponding starting offsets, which is essential for safe truncation and replica synchronization.\n\n**LogStartOffset Tracking** is implemented in UnifiedLog (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/UnifiedLog.java) which maintains both the local log start offset and the leader's log start offset. The logStartOffset field tracks the earliest offset in the log, which is crucial for knowing which records can be safely deleted.\n\n**ISR Management** (in-sync replica shrinking and expanding) is handled in Partition (core/src/main/scala/kafka/cluster/Partition.scala) with several key case classes:\n- PendingShrinkIsr: represents replicas that are out of sync and need to be removed from the ISR\n- PendingExpandIsr: represents replicas that have caught up and can be added back to the ISR\n- CommittedPartitionState: holds the committed ISR state\n- maybeShrinkIsr(): method that checks and initiates ISR shrinking when needed\n\n## Supporting Infrastructure\n\n**ReplicaManager** (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/ReplicaManager.scala) is the main orchestrator that manages all replicas for a broker, coordinates with ReplicaFetcherManager, and handles ISR changes through AlterPartitionManager.\n\n**AbstractFetcherThread** (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/AbstractFetcherThread.scala) provides the base implementation for fetcher threads, including the critical getOffsetTruncationState() method that determines truncation points based on leader epoch information.\n\n**ReplicaFetcherManager** (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/ReplicaFetcherManager.scala) manages the pool of ReplicaFetcherThread instances, creating and managing fetchers for different leader brokers. It extends AbstractFetcherManager.\n\n**RemoteLeaderEndPoint** (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/RemoteLeaderEndPoint.scala) handles communication with remote leader brokers, sending fetch requests and receiving responses with epoch information.\n\n**LocalLeaderEndPoint** (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/LocalLeaderEndPoint.scala) handles communication for local leaders when both leader and follower are on the same broker.\n\n## Epoch and Checkpoint Management\n\n**LeaderEpochCheckpointFile** (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/checkpoint/LeaderEpochCheckpointFile.java) persists the leader epoch cache to disk, ensuring epoch information survives broker restarts.\n\n**EpochEntry** (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/EpochEntry.java) is a simple data class representing a single epoch entry with epoch number and starting offset.\n\n**LogSegment.recover()** (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/LogSegment.java) uses the LeaderEpochFileCache during log recovery to ensure correct truncation based on epoch boundaries.\n\n**LogLoader** (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/LogLoader.java) loads logs at startup with proper epoch cache initialization and recovery.\n\n## Log Append Information\n\n**LogAppendInfo** (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/LogAppendInfo.java) tracks the logStartOffset when appending records to the log, maintaining consistency with replica state.\n\n## Alter Partition Management\n\n**DefaultAlterPartitionManager** (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/AlterPartitionManager.scala) communicates with the controller to update ISR changes (shrink/expand operations) initiated by the broker.\n\n## Log Directory Migration\n\n**ReplicaAlterLogDirsThread** (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/ReplicaAlterLogDirsThread.scala) and **ReplicaAlterLogDirsManager** (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/ReplicaAlterLogDirsManager.scala) handle moving replicas between log directories while maintaining epoch boundaries and log consistency.\n\nThe entire protocol works as follows: The ReplicaFetcherThread periodically fetches data from the leader's RemoteLeaderEndPoint, using the current highWatermark and logStartOffset. It receives the leader's epoch information and uses getOffsetTruncationState() to determine if truncation is needed based on epoch mismatch. The LeaderEpochFileCache maintains a consistent view of epoch history for safe truncation decisions. When replicas fall behind, Partition's maybeShrinkIsr() is called, which creates a PendingShrinkIsr state and submits it to DefaultAlterPartitionManager for controller approval. When replicas catch up, PendingExpandIsr is created similarly. This distributed protocol ensures strong consistency guarantees across the cluster."
